{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/child-maltreatment-recognition-management/recognition/fabricated-or-induced-illness/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"cc833a45-7dd6-55f1-bc2a-90a17e88f83c","slug":"fabricated-or-induced-illness","fullItemName":"Fabricated or induced illness","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field c539b17e-0f02-4077-bf40-bb30242576a3 --><h2>When should I suspect or consider fabricated or induced illness?</h2><!-- end field c539b17e-0f02-4077-bf40-bb30242576a3 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 1a33339e-01e4-436f-8741-7fed5ec180e0 --><!-- begin field 4477f5bc-403a-4061-ad00-3200c4b03210 --><ul><li><strong><em>Suspect </em>fabricated or induced illness if t</strong><strong>he child's history, presentation, examination, or investigation does not match a recognized clinical picture, plus at least one of the following is present:</strong><ul><li>Reported symptoms and signs only appear or reappear when the parent or carer is present and/or are only observed by the parent/carer</li><li>An inexplicably poor response to prescribed medication or other treatment.</li><li>New symptoms are reported as soon as previous ones have resolved.</li><li>A history of clinically unlikely events (for example, infants with a history of very large blood losses who do not become unwell or anaemic).</li><li>Despite a definitive clinical opinion, further opinions from both primary and secondary care continue to be sought and disputed by the parent/carer and the child continues to be presented for investigation and treatment with a range of signs and symptoms.</li><li>The child's normal daily activities (for example, school attendance) are being compromised, or the child is using aids to daily living (for example, wheelchairs) more than would be expected for any medical condition that the child has.<ul><li>Note that inappropriate substances, including prescribed and non-prescribed drugs, may be given to induce symptoms of illness. For more information, please see the section on <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/child-maltreatment-recognition-management/recognition/physical-abuse/\">physical abuse</a>.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong><em>Consider</em> fabricated or induced illness if:</strong><ul><li>The child's history, presentation, examination and investigation does not match a recognized clinical picture.</li><li>There are repeated apparent life-threatening events where the onset is witnessed only by one parent or carer and a medical explanation has not been identified.<ul><li>Note that fabricated or induced illness is a possible explanation even if the child has a past or concurrent physical or psychological condition.</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 4477f5bc-403a-4061-ad00-3200c4b03210 --><!-- end item 1a33339e-01e4-436f-8741-7fed5ec180e0 -->","topic":{"id":"399c706c-d925-5357-8bd0-fb82cd95ee01","topicId":"7e199db4-11c4-42e5-8f2d-878014e6b1ee","topicName":"Child maltreatment - recognition and management","slug":"child-maltreatment-recognition-management","lastRevised":"Last revised in January 2019","chapters":[{"id":"44455b04-f8f9-5618-936e-0f3ee64eff15","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"adf16a06-53ba-50f6-b77c-723ecd9b3220","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"d5b2b953-c8cc-5be0-b514-38c4c95eca62","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"727476e5-0ff0-56a5-a9b2-7dc9ce1c5de4","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"7d13d77e-1923-5987-b363-d99c2e6646bb","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"d65e5f53-9b67-5099-ae1a-7ed5f26cc490","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"fb949766-5f45-5bbd-bacd-cabd51c7a0c5","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"9